[Thank you.]</i>

5
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:25,710
<i>[Tomomi Oikawa]</i>

6
00:00:25,710 --> 00:00:28,040
<i>[I have a feeling that I can sing well today...]</i>

7
00:00:29,180 --> 00:00:31,550
<i>[Award - Ms. Tomomi Oikawa]</i>

8
00:00:35,140 --> 00:00:37,330
<i>[To be continued]</i>

9
00:00:56,330 --> 00:01:01,340
Ms. Oikawa, have you decided on the theme of your next series?

10
00:01:01,340 --> 00:01:03,240
I'm still thinking.

11
00:01:03,240 --> 00:01:07,010
Why not do something dramatic so we can make it into a movie?

12
00:01:07,010 --> 00:01:10,840
You know that's not my principle.

13
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:13,630
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

14
00:01:16,250 --> 00:01:18,390
Oh, right.

15
00:01:20,270 --> 00:01:25,520
Here are the materials you asked for.

16
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:30,190
And... I brought your fan letters we received.

17
00:01:30,190 --> 00:01:33,630
One of them wants to meet you, but don't worry about it.

18
00:01:33,630 --> 00:01:36,670
- Someone wants to meet me?
- Yes.

19
00:01:36,670 --> 00:01:39,870
"I'm writing to you because I want you to listen

20
00:01:39,870 --> 00:01:42,310
the story about my friends and me."

21
00:01:42,310 --> 00:01:47,120
"About the relationship, I and two of my friends have had for 35 years."

22
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,590
Here.

23
00:01:51,590 --> 00:01:56,080
She thinks her life is so interesting that she wants you to novelize it. We get that often.

24
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:59,680
It's usually not very interesting.

25
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:02,640
Anyway, please think about making your novels into movies.

26
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:06,640
<i>[Sorry for the sudden letter. I'm a fan of yours.]</i>

27
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:08,530
<i>[To Ms. Tomomi Oikawa]</i>

28
00:02:08,530 --> 00:02:10,890
<i>[Yuri Totsuka]</i>

29
00:02:12,320 --> 00:02:14,820
<i>[Yuri Totsuka]</i>

30
00:02:56,910 --> 00:02:59,720
You are the Yuri Totsuka?

31
00:02:59,790 --> 00:03:03,750
Yes. Nice to meet you.

32
00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:14,120
Certainly.

33
00:03:17,320 --> 00:03:21,420
I didn't think you would agree to meet me.

34
00:03:21,420 --> 00:03:26,610
There surely are a lot of people who ask me to hear their life story

35
00:03:26,610 --> 00:03:30,350
I usually turn down that kind of request.

36
00:03:31,070 --> 00:03:36,980
But you don't want to talk about your life story.

37
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:41,210
It's about you and your friends, right?

38
00:03:42,470 --> 00:03:48,960
Many of your work is about the relationship between women.

39
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:52,120
So, I thought you would be interested.

40
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:58,920
You said in the letter that one of your friends has pancreatic cancer.

41
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:00,620
- Is it true?
- Yes.

42
00:04:00,620 --> 00:04:03,470
That's why I wanted to meet you as soon as possible.

43
00:04:03,470 --> 00:04:06,770
Before she passes away.

44
00:04:10,900 --> 00:04:16,440
Even if you are asking me to write a novel about it, I can't promise anything.

45
00:04:16,440 --> 00:04:20,190
I'm an entertainment novelist and I only write fiction.

46
00:04:20,190 --> 00:04:24,830
That's all right. I just want you to listen.

47
00:04:34,590 --> 00:04:36,200
May I?

48
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:37,740
Please.

49
00:04:46,120 --> 00:04:51,160
As I wrote in the letter, what I'd like to talk about

50
00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:55,490
is the relationship I've had with

51
00:04:55,490 --> 00:04:58,570
two of my friends for 35 years.

52
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:07,570
In order to protect each other, the three of us...

53
00:05:11,570 --> 00:05:13,870
killed someone.

54
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:31,490
It all started when we were 16 years old.

55
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:36,350
Back then...

56
00:05:36,350 --> 00:05:40,700
I hated myself more than anyone in the world.

57
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:49,350
<i>- Sorry.
- It's okay.</i>

58
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:52,360
<i>- Rinako, are you all right?
- Yeah.</i>

59
00:05:55,550 --> 00:06:00,650
I despised myself more than anyone in the world.

60
00:06:03,610 --> 00:06:09,630
That's when the three of us met.

61
00:06:10,590 --> 00:06:15,550
<i>[Fuji Hikari Complex Map]</i>

62
00:06:48,180 --> 00:06:50,500
Maho Sakazaki and...

63
00:06:56,460 --> 00:06:58,380
Satoko Hino.

64
00:07:29,660 --> 00:07:35,770
That day was the beginning of

65
00:07:35,770 --> 00:07:38,950
the chain of murders.

66
00:07:50,680 --> 00:07:59,150
<i>[INFLUENCE - Episode 1]</i>

67
00:07:59,150 --> 00:08:02,130
<i>[November 1984, Shizuoka]</i>

68
00:08:02,130 --> 00:08:06,170
<i>[Asanodai High School]</i>

69
00:08:12,920 --> 00:08:16,270
- Don't be fascinated by her.
- I'm not.

70
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:20,650
Who is she?

71
00:08:20,650 --> 00:08:24,150
- She is a transfer student from Tokyo.
- Yeah?

72
00:08:35,900 --> 00:08:39,050
<i>[Books - Magazines]</i>

73
00:08:46,600 --> 00:08:48,120
Hey.

74
00:08:50,400 --> 00:08:52,430
Aren't you going to buy that?

75
00:08:54,970 --> 00:08:57,640
I'm not.

76
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:02,020
I'm sorry.

77
00:09:08,450 --> 00:09:11,740
<i>It'll be 370 yen.</i>

78
00:09:12,770 --> 00:09:15,550
<i>370 yen it is.</i>

79
00:09:15,550 --> 00:09:17,800
<i>Thank you.</i>

80
00:09:24,700 --> 00:09:28,470
I'm a faster reader. Do you want to borrow it when I'm done?

81
00:09:28,470 --> 00:09:30,490
What?

82
00:09:30,490 --> 00:09:32,490
You don't want to read it?

83
00:09:33,590 --> 00:09:35,700
I do.

84
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:38,640
Then, wait while I read it there.

85
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:40,900
What? Now?

86
00:09:48,670 --> 00:09:52,520
<i>[Mahiru's Experience: story and illustration by Naomi Nishi]</i>

87
00:09:52,520 --> 00:09:54,590
Here you go.

88
00:09:54,590 --> 00:09:56,980
You really do read fast.

89
00:09:57,990 --> 00:09:59,520
Did you move into the complex?

90
00:09:59,520 --> 00:10:02,090
Yes, Building 2.

91
00:10:02,090 --> 00:10:05,450
I see. I live in Building 13.

92
00:10:05,450 --> 00:10:07,990
Yeah. I've seen you.

93
00:10:07,990 --> 00:10:10,930
I knew we lived in the same place and go to the same high school.

94
00:10:14,610 --> 00:10:17,030
- Aren't you going to read it?
- Right.

95
00:10:24,080 --> 00:10:26,470
That part was funny.

96
00:10:33,490 --> 00:10:37,610
The earlier works of this manga artist are more interesting.

97
00:10:41,560 --> 00:10:43,700
You can borrow these.

98
00:10:44,450 --> 00:10:49,830
And... these novels, too.

99
00:10:50,570 --> 00:10:52,470
Thank you.

100
00:10:55,590 --> 00:10:57,850
Is orange juice okay?

101
00:10:57,850 --> 00:10:59,510
Yeah.

102
00:11:10,860 --> 00:11:12,460
What?

103
00:11:13,480 --> 00:11:16,690
I've never seen a person who makes fresh juice at home.

104
00:11:17,990 --> 00:11:20,890
Store-bought juice has additives, so...

105
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:40,510
I hear you've been hanging out with the girl who moved into Building 2.

106
00:11:41,480 --> 00:11:45,520
Mrs. Eguchi next door saw you two together.

107
00:11:45,520 --> 00:11:47,770
Did you visit her place?

108
00:11:47,770 --> 00:11:49,990
I did. Why?

109
00:11:49,990 --> 00:11:53,560
I bet their furniture looked expensive.

110
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:55,470
How do you know?

111
00:11:55,470 --> 00:11:58,890
Mrs. Yoshikawa in Building 2 told me.

112
00:11:58,890 --> 00:12:01,960
She saw movers were carrying gorgeous furniture when they moved in.

113
00:12:01,960 --> 00:12:03,440
I told you that, right?

114
00:12:03,440 --> 00:12:05,710
What? They are rich?

115
00:12:05,710 --> 00:12:08,780
Well, it's just the mother and the child.

116
00:12:08,780 --> 00:12:12,340
Her husband was the president of a company in Tokyo,

117
00:12:12,340 --> 00:12:15,490
but she came back to her hometown after the divorce.

118
00:12:15,490 --> 00:12:19,150
I heard she got a large amount of alimony.

119
00:12:19,150 --> 00:12:22,090
I guess the reason for the divorce was the husband's affair.

120
00:12:22,090 --> 00:12:25,790
It's just a rumor, right? Don't say that.

121
00:12:25,790 --> 00:12:29,790
She said so herself.

122
00:12:29,790 --> 00:12:32,810
She was giving out expensive sweets to her neighbors when she moved in.

123
00:12:32,810 --> 00:12:36,220
And told them she was getting a lot of child support payment.

124
00:12:36,220 --> 00:12:38,670
She brought in expensive furniture to show off,

125
00:12:38,670 --> 00:12:42,660
but she lives in this shabby complex after all.

126
00:12:44,530 --> 00:12:47,590
It's good to be the same, Yuri.

127
00:12:47,590 --> 00:12:50,380
People look at you with curious eyes when you stand out.

128
00:12:50,380 --> 00:12:54,150
So, it's better to do the same with the others.

129
00:12:54,150 --> 00:12:56,410
Isn't that right?

130
00:13:03,230 --> 00:13:05,860
<i>[Freshman, Class 8]</i>

131
00:13:29,770 --> 00:13:32,730
I thought she was beautiful and I liked her at first,

132
00:13:32,730 --> 00:13:35,340
but she is different.

133
00:13:35,340 --> 00:13:36,920
Different?

134
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:40,870
You better stay away from her, too.

135
00:14:20,740 --> 00:14:22,410
Maho.

136
00:14:29,550 --> 00:14:31,850
Let's go home together today.

137
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:43,990
Why did you come to our school?

138
00:14:43,990 --> 00:14:48,770
You could have gone to a better school.

139
00:14:48,770 --> 00:14:51,880
I wanted to go to a school within walking distance.

140
00:14:51,880 --> 00:14:54,880
I was groped on the train before.

141
00:14:57,530 --> 00:15:01,630
I had so many lessons after school before I moved here.

142
00:15:01,630 --> 00:15:05,230
English, piano, and ballet.

143
00:15:05,230 --> 00:15:08,630
I liked ballet, so I didn't want to quit.

144
00:15:09,320 --> 00:15:11,580
I see.

145
00:15:12,350 --> 00:15:15,200
You didn't laugh.

146
00:15:15,200 --> 00:15:17,720
- What?
- At the park.

147
00:15:17,720 --> 00:15:20,900
You saw me practicing ballet, right?

148
00:15:22,810 --> 00:15:25,070
It was beautiful.

149
00:15:25,070 --> 00:15:27,040
I was happy.

150
00:15:29,020 --> 00:15:34,390
My mom doesn't like to admit defeat.

151
00:15:36,420 --> 00:15:39,730
She has her hands full protecting her pride,

152
00:15:39,730 --> 00:15:43,370
and she can't care about my feelings.

153
00:15:47,090 --> 00:15:51,390
So, I have to fight on my own.

154
00:15:53,800 --> 00:15:58,280
I don't want to change myself because others don't accept me for who I am.

155
00:16:01,850 --> 00:16:04,480
I don't want my fate to get the best of me.

156
00:16:19,700 --> 00:16:21,830
Oh, Yuri. You're back.

157
00:16:21,830 --> 00:16:24,650
You two have become friends, I see.

158
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:27,330
I heard your mother got a job.

159
00:16:27,330 --> 00:16:30,300
It must be hard for her since she'd been a stay-at-home mom.

160
00:16:30,300 --> 00:16:32,520
Where does she work?

161
00:16:33,400 --> 00:16:35,060
Where?

162
00:16:38,030 --> 00:16:41,730
At the supermarket near the station? I know they were hiring.

163
00:16:48,570 --> 00:16:51,740
<i>It's good to be the same...</i>

164
00:16:51,740 --> 00:16:56,310
I guess what my mother was trying to say was

165
00:16:56,310 --> 00:16:59,920
you can't be accepted otherwise.

166
00:17:00,990 --> 00:17:03,140
I understand.

167
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:06,330
It's not limited to housing complexes and schools.

168
00:17:06,330 --> 00:17:08,400
In such closed communities,

169
00:17:08,400 --> 00:17:12,550
people try to eliminate those who are different.

170
00:17:15,470 --> 00:17:18,870
But I think Maho was lucky.

171
00:17:18,870 --> 00:17:22,430
Because you had the courage to talk to her.

172
00:17:23,980 --> 00:17:26,700
That's not it.

173
00:17:28,760 --> 00:17:33,110
I talked to her instead of turning away from her,

174
00:17:34,300 --> 00:17:36,810
because I had regrets.

175
00:17:37,730 --> 00:17:39,410
Regrets?

176
00:17:41,670 --> 00:17:44,160
Once before,

177
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:47,330
I had abandoned my friend

178
00:17:47,330 --> 00:17:49,820
and left her to die.

179
00:17:54,500 --> 00:17:59,730
That is my other friend.

180
00:18:00,940 --> 00:18:02,640
Satoko.

181
00:18:11,720 --> 00:18:14,300
- I feel sorry for him.
- I know, right?

182
00:18:15,710 --> 00:18:17,800
They're bullying someone again.

183
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:34,230
Do you know her?

184
00:18:35,050 --> 00:18:38,160
We grew up together in the same complex.

185
00:18:38,790 --> 00:18:40,660
We used to play together when we were in elementary school.

186
00:18:40,660 --> 00:18:42,410
<i> Pineapple.
<i>[October, 1975]</i></i>

187
00:18:42,410 --> 00:18:46,290
<i>Ruby.</i>

188
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:50,350
<i>- Can I go to your place today, Yuri?
- Sure.</i>

189
00:18:50,350 --> 00:18:55,920
<i>Oh, my mom said she would get me a cherry stick.</i>

190
00:18:57,040 --> 00:19:00,780
<i>Yuri! Let's play together.</i>

191
00:19:02,240 --> 00:19:03,650
<i>Welcome!</i>

192
00:19:03,650 --> 00:19:07,430
<i>Yuri, Satoko is here.</i>

193
00:19:11,710 --> 00:19:13,490
<i>What's wrong?</i>

194
00:19:14,740 --> 00:19:18,100
<i>That's Yuri's grandpa. He's visiting us.</i>

195
00:19:18,100 --> 00:19:20,150
<i>So, you are Satoko.</i>

196
00:19:20,150 --> 00:19:22,030
<i>Thank you for being friends with</i>

197
00:19:22,030 --> 00:19:24,300
<i>Yuri.</i>

198
00:19:29,510 --> 00:19:33,120
<i>Are you sleeping here tonight?</i>

199
00:19:33,120 --> 00:19:37,910
<i>Ah... Thank you, I will.</i>

200
00:19:37,910 --> 00:19:41,360
<i>You are sleeping with your grandpa, Yuri?</i>

201
00:19:41,360 --> 00:19:42,970
<i>Hm?</i>

202
00:19:42,970 --> 00:19:45,290
<i>She's not sleeping with me.</i>

203
00:19:45,290 --> 00:19:49,910
<i>When grandpa is staying, Yuri sleeps with me.</i>

204
00:19:49,910 --> 00:19:54,490
<i>But girls are supposed to sleep with their grandpa.</i>

205
00:19:55,330 --> 00:19:57,200
<i>Girls are?</i>

206
00:19:57,200 --> 00:20:01,100
<i>Do you sleep with your grandpa, Satoko?</i>

207
00:20:01,100 --> 00:20:06,060
<i>Because Mom said a girl should sleep with her grandpa.</i>

208
00:20:06,970 --> 00:20:08,870
<i>Is that...</i>

209
00:20:08,870 --> 00:20:12,090
<i>By sleeping with, do you mean in the same room?</i>

210
00:20:12,090 --> 00:20:15,510
<i>Or in the same bed?</i>

211
00:20:15,510 --> 00:20:17,200
<i>In the same bed.</i>

212
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:20,990
<i>Because girls sleep with their grandpas.</i>

213
00:20:20,990 --> 00:20:22,730
<i>That's what I was told.</i>

214
00:20:31,350 --> 00:20:33,900
<i>No way. You are overthinking.</i>

215
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:36,350
<i>But she repeated it many times.</i>

216
00:20:36,350 --> 00:20:39,720
<i>Girls sleep with their grandpas.</i>

217
00:20:39,720 --> 00:20:42,060
<i>That's weird, right?</i>

218
00:20:42,060 --> 00:20:44,000
<i>The floor plan is the same as ours.</i>

219
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:47,320
<i>Satoko's parents and her little brother sleep in this room,</i>

220
00:20:47,320 --> 00:20:51,490
<i>and she sleeps with her grandfather in the other room.</i>

221
00:20:51,490 --> 00:20:53,120
<i>Why don't you ask her mother?</i>

222
00:20:53,120 --> 00:20:55,480
<i>How am I supposed to ask her?</i>

223
00:20:55,480 --> 00:20:58,630
<i>"I heard your daughter sleeps with her grandfather,</i>

224
00:20:58,630 --> 00:21:02,360
<i>but is he doing something wrong to her?"</i>

225
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:04,360
<i>That's not good.</i>

226
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:06,250
<i>If I was wrong, it would cause trouble.</i>

227
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:11,480
<i>And if it was true, I wouldn't want to get involved.</i>

228
00:21:11,480 --> 00:21:16,570
<i>Anyway, we should keep Yuri away from that girl.</i>

229
00:21:16,570 --> 00:21:21,050
<i>It could be a bad influence on Yuri.</i>

230
00:21:25,740 --> 00:21:27,080
<i>Listen.</i>

231
00:21:27,080 --> 00:21:31,080
<i>Don't ever go to Satoko's place.</i>

232
00:21:31,080 --> 00:21:33,180
<i>Even if she invites you, you have to say no.</i>

233
00:21:33,180 --> 00:21:37,730
<i>If you want to play with her, stay here, or somewhere where adults are around.</i>

234
00:21:37,730 --> 00:21:39,340
<i>Understood?</i>

235
00:21:56,060 --> 00:21:59,260
<i>Oh, Yuri. Wait for a moment.</i>

236
00:21:59,260 --> 00:22:01,930
<i>Auntie?</i>

237
00:22:02,800 --> 00:22:04,280
<i>What is it?</i>

238
00:22:06,080 --> 00:22:09,260
<i>Did Satoko cause you any trouble?</i>

239
00:22:09,920 --> 00:22:13,590
<i>She's good for nothing.</i>

240
00:22:14,450 --> 00:22:19,600
<i>Ah, Yu. What's the matter?</i>

241
00:22:35,450 --> 00:22:38,130
<i>Yuri, what's the matter?</i>

242
00:22:56,030 --> 00:23:00,700
I was unable to help her out, then...

243
00:23:00,700 --> 00:23:04,500
I became estranged from Satoko.

244
00:23:04,500 --> 00:23:09,810
But it wasn't your fault.

245
00:23:09,810 --> 00:23:11,720
You were only an elementary student.

246
00:23:11,720 --> 00:23:15,010
The people who forsook Satoko

247
00:23:15,010 --> 00:23:18,970
were your parents and your grandfather.

248
00:23:20,360 --> 00:23:24,610
I can't say I'm completely innocent.

249
00:23:26,390 --> 00:23:31,650
Turning a blind eye is also a sin.

250
00:23:34,680 --> 00:23:38,210
The most regrettable sin I've committed was...

251
00:23:38,210 --> 00:23:43,640
that I left Satoko in the living hell.

252
00:23:44,180 --> 00:23:48,790
And yet, I pretended to be her friend.

253
00:23:51,940 --> 00:23:55,800
You, Maho, and Satoko...

